        </svg>
        <span class="key-takeaways__title">Key Takeaways — {stateName} Probate</span>
      </div>
      <div class="key-takeaways__body">
        <ul class="key-takeaways__list">
          <li>A will does not avoid probate in {stateName} — it runs probate with instructions.</li>
          <li>{stateName} probate typically takes <strong>{guide.probate_timeline}</strong> and costs approximately <strong>{guide.probate_cost_example}</strong> in combined attorney and executor fees on a $500,000 estate.</li>
          <li>Probate fees are calculated on gross asset value, not net equity — a $800K home with a $400K mortgage still generates fees on the full $800K.</li>
          <li>Estates under <strong>{guide.small_estate_limit}</strong> in personal property may qualify for simplified affidavit procedures (California Probate Code § 13100).</li>
          <li>Beneficiary designations, joint tenancy, TOD designations, and living trusts all bypass {stateName} probate.</li>
          <li>{stateName} Revocable Transfer on Death Deeds (TOD deeds for real property) are available and permanent as of 2022.</li>
        </ul>
